events.event_name: FAO Food Price Index January 2026 Release
events.description: The FAO Food Price Index slipped 0.4% to 123.9 points in January 2026, marking a fifth consecutive monthly decline.

facts.fact_text: The FAO Food Price Index fell 0.4% to 123.9 points in January 2026.

evidences.evidence_text: The FAO Food Price Index slipped 0.4% to 123.9 points in January 2026, marking a fifth consecutive monthly decline and a fresh low level since August 2024.

facts.fact_text: Dairy costs declined by 5% in January 2026.

evidences.evidence_text: Also, dairy cost tumbled 5%, the seventh consecutive monthly decline, driven largely by lower world cheese and butter prices.

facts.fact_text: Meat prices declined 0.4%, reaching their lowest level since May 2025.

evidences.evidence_text: Meat declined 0.4%, the lowest since May 2025, mainly reflecting lower pig meat prices

facts.fact_text: Cereal costs increased by 0.2% in January 2026.

evidences.evidence_text: In contrast, cereal costs edged up 0.2%, reaching the highest since May 2025.

facts.fact_text: Oil prices rose 2.1% due to higher palm, soy, and sunflower oil prices.

evidences.evidence_text: Oil prices also jumped 2.1%, amid higher world prices of palm, soy and sunflower oils

claims.claim_text: Global sugar supplies are expected to increase in the current season.
claims.author: FAO

evidences.evidence_text: driven by expectations of increased global sugar supplies in the current season

claims.claim_text: A significant production rebound is anticipated for sugar in India.

evidences.evidence_text: largely underpinned by a significant production rebound anticipated in India

claims.claim_text: Thailand has favourable prospects for sugar production.
